nuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://archive.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: KILLING ASTEROIDS - SAVING EARTH</span><hr size=1> The K-T boundary event gets all the attention, because of the 'Tyrant Lizards ', but it was not the only, or the biggest extinction event in the fossil record. One of the biggest was the end of the Permian era, with over 90% extinction. I don't recall any advanced creatures, but it's fairly clear that through life's history over 98% of all the species that have ever lived were wiped out very rapidly in one event or another.<br>
<br>
A common criticism of evolutionary theory drives me batty; the mistaken assertion that &quot;all of a sudden&quot;, life crawled out of primordial soup or that &quot;suddenly&quot; apes became humans. No, it takes a very long time.<br>
However, the alternate viewpoint, that pure Darwinian survival of the fittest means that species go on for eons with a tiny mutation here &amp; there granting superiority until eventually the new form is dominant, doesn't fit the evidence either -not as a completely inclusive rule.<br>
<br>
What the fossil record shows all too often, is that over several tens (maybe a few hundreds) of millions of years, forms diversify, filling every ecological niche, with competing species from all sorts of genera swarming in all sorts of environments. Then, &quot;all of a sudden&quot;, almost everything is wiped out. All over the Earth, most species in most niches are gone in a startlingly short time.<br>
A few survivors in this environment, a few in this, find themselves alone with very few competitors. Then again, over the next several or many millions of years, species diversify and fill in all niches with amazing varieties competing for superiority.<br>
Then again, all of a sudden; &quot;Whoom!&quot;, everything but a few survivors here &amp; there are gone.<br>
<br>
Again and again, the fossil record shows this sequence. Everything alive is a descendent of something which has survived mass extinctions.<br>
If the development of life is something which happens on planets when the conditions are right, there's no reason that some self-replicating complex chains of chemicals wasn't completely sterilised when the early Earth was struggling out of the planetary formation process. We know that there's evidence for life surprisingly early. There may have been earlier forms, which we know nothing about.<br>
<br>
Evidence for life on Earth before 3.8 billion years ago<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/mars/nn961106.htm">www.fas.org/mars/nn961106.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/uk/scotland/newsid_1111000/1111088.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/uk/scotland/newsid_1111000/1111088.stm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2001/ast17jan_1.htm?list19855">science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2001/ast17jan_1.htm?list19855</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
&quot;... ancient stream deposits indicate that Earth developed continents and water -- perhaps even oceans and environments in which microbial life could emerge -- 4.3 billion to 4.4 billion years ago, remarkably soon after our planet formed.&quot;<br>
<br>
Added to this, is the amazing hypothesis called &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://panspermia.org/">Panspermia</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot; where the possibility is raised that life can transplant itself via meteorite impacts.<br>
<br>
The only force which fits the description of what could cause these extinction events, is planetary impact. Since the acceptance of evidence of an impact cause for the Arizona crater, and then the Chixulub crater, all of the so called &quot;cryptovolcanic craters&quot; have been identified as definate impact craters (the reasoning behind the term &quot;cryptovolcanic&quot; was thus: they are volcanic, all right, we just can't see the volcanic causes. We'll call it &quot;Crypto&quot;, or hidden volcanism. Anything but that dirty word &quot;catastrophism&quot;).<br>
Space probes also show that the entire history of the inner solar system is one of random, violent impacts.<br>
<br>
Call it far out scare tactics, call it hype &amp; hysteria over something which hits every few million generations, but we are in a shooting gallery. Every year, there are many aerial blasts which, if over a city, could cause massive destruction. The Tunguskka blast of 1908 was an average hit; about 15Mt.<br>
There are arguments that an impact was only one out of several events which caused an extinction event, but an impact fits the description better than anything else.<br>
There's strong reason to believe that no volcanic release event can be over 1000 Mt, but that's only a small-ish impact event.<br>
Very large impacts make the worst industrial pollution seem like nothing.<br>
First is the scorching of vast areas. The aeroentry alone can scorch a continent, and the following impact does the same over a larger area, followed by the global reentry of fragments thrown by the splash. These are each &amp; every one a separate impact, with similar local devastation. The dust thrown globally in the stratoshpere is only one part of the worst effects.<br>
Then, large energy releases cause combustion of atmosphere, with familiar release of nitric &amp; nitrous compounds. These react with H2O &amp; O2 to form various acids more toxic than the worst man made acid rain. Similarly toxic compounds are caused by the sulfur compounds in the entering body itself.<br>
These chemical compounds also cause release of metallic ions &amp; molecules from topsoil, and the dissolution of carbonate rocks, adding to the global toxicity. Many of the metals found in boundary layers are not only from the asteroid, but leached from soils.<br>
In addition to the acidic effects of such compounds, they are very efficient sunlight blockers, intensifying the global sunlight shortage. It may very well be too dark for vision for a long time.<br>
<br>
After the global ice age caused by the impact, the environment has to contend with these chemicals and the CO2 from carbonate rocks in the form of global greenhouse warming. Several of the nitrogen &amp; sulfur compounds are efficient greenhouse gasses, and they stay around during the ice age.<br>
<br>
It's common to see the assertion that there's only one recorded case of a person being harmed by a meteorite (the woman in Alabama, 1928?). <br>
This actually means that there's only one case of a person being harmed, while acceptable forensics were available to definately prove that an impact was to blame. If you accept other people's accounts, there's plenty of precedent.<br>
<br>
It is common today to hear that Humanity is another kind of extinction force, and is causing the worse of all mass extinction events, the 6th mass extinction event in the planet's history.<br>
 On the other hand, there's every bit as much evidence that we should be in another ice age now. Recent history -the entire range of human history- is shown by ice cores &amp; geological evidence from around the globe to be a very brief &amp; anomalous trend. The history for the last several million years is of only brief transient periods of warmth, with the longest times spent under global ice.<br>
The &quot;mini-Ice Ages&quot; of the 1600-1700s gave warning. It's entirely possible that without the advent of largescale wood &amp; coal burning in the 1700s that we'd be entering an ice age now.<br>
All of human history seems to have been allowed by the strange warming in the last tens of thousands of years.<br>
<br>
Given all this, it seems to be some hubris to say that Humankind is the worst thing which ever happened to the Earth.<br>
I get tired of hearing this implication that humans are a virus scum, and the Earth would be better off without us (Frequently it's more than implied, it is a definate statement and I always stamp it out whenever possible).<br>
<br>
John Lewis From &quot;Mining the Sky&quot;:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  As long as the human population remains as pitifully small as it is today, we shall be severely limited in what we can accomplish.<br>
 Human intelligence is the key to the future: human beings are not, as some would have it, a form of pollution. Having only one Einstein, one Hokusai, one Mozart, one DaVinci, one Shankara,... is not enough. We need -and can have- a million times as many. We need intelligence, wisdom, compassion, and excellence. These godlike traits are manifested in the physical universe only by life, and in the biological universe, only by intelligent life.<br>
Life is not a cancer of matter; it is matter's trancendance of itself.<br>
We would be quite wrong to conclude that the asteroid belt, or solar power... is the ultimate resource. Intelligent life, once liberated by the resources of space, is the greatest resource of the solar system.<br>
The material and energy resources of the solar system allow mankind an infinite future: we can not only break free of the surly bonds of the Earth, but break free of the Sun and escape its fate.<br>
The fulfillment of time &amp; space is matter; the fulfillment of matter is life; the highest fulfillment of life is unbounded intelligence &amp; compassion.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There is a radical fringe group of the environmental movement which should be called the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://vhemt.org/">Voluntary Human Extinction Movement</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> -except they never do us the favor of mass-suicide, and you never hear of them surgically sacrificing their reproductive organs for the greater good.<br>
<br>
Our opportunity is to find a way to allow growth of human resources without killing everything else off. Biodiversity is too precious, because (unless we find something living &quot;out there&quot;) it's the only example of life in this universe.<br>
<br>
Consider the following article:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  One interesting way to look at space colonization is via the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://lifesci3.arc.nasa.gov/SpaceSettlement/Basics/wwwwh.html#mother">Mother Earth metaphor</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
With this metaphor we compare the biosphere to a pregnant woman.<br>
This implies that we think of the biosphere as a single organism, which is consistent with the Gaia hypothesis proposed by Dr. Lovelock.<br>
In the following discussion, remember that this is only a metaphor.<br>
Consider the biosphere as a pregnant woman, with the twist that she doesn't know she's pregnant and doesn't know that pregnancy exists -- or that children exist.<br>
This is the condition most of us find ourselves in since space colonization is not widely believed as a realistic concept.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Scarcity of resources &amp; room for growth is not a fact. It is an illusion borne of ignorance. We do not live on only one Earth. We are not nearing the end of human history. If we like, we are at the beginning of the newest phase of frontier expansion with infinite prospects before us.<br>
As far as we can know, most of the universe is a waste of frightening hostility, but with some engineering, we can make places for life to prosper.<br>
Freeman Dyson said that once we start the break out into space, there's no reason that we shouldn't live on past the Sun, and until the end of the universe. Maybe we can do something about the 5 billion year span expected for the Sun -He also said that we may find ourselves in the position to do something about the limited time for this universe, too...<br>
In the 1970s, several studies showed that there's no new inventions needed to start; no fundamental new discoveries in processes or techniques need to be made. While there are several points of asteroid mining or Lunar resources use which are &quot;gray&quot; (we don't know the _best_ ways to do a step or process) we do know of several ways, each of which would work.<br>
<br>
One seeming objection to this I hear is the so-called &quot;disposable Earth&quot; philosophy: (Sarcastically) &quot;We'll just go off to some other place in space after we've wasted this Earth.&quot; This never comes seriously from someone enthusiastic &amp; knowledgeable about the possibilities in space; Usually it comes from someone who has never read of the possibilities, doesn't like it, and thinks others (whom they couldn't possibly like or agree with at all) could feel this way.<br>
It has _never_ come from someone who has been in space -quite the reverse. The fragility &amp; infinite value of Earth &amp; its life is imperative.<br>
Note that I say nothing of what people should or will believe, and I don't require a new stage of human thinking or evolution. On the other hand, restricting future human civilizations to the limited surface of this one small planet implies urgent need for crushing controls on human consumption &amp; resource use. With space resources and industries having been moved off planet, the Earth could indeed support a human population of 15 billion, all in better conditions than any but the richest of today. The nearest available space resources could support a population of hundreds of billions in space settlements.<br>
<br>
To tie topics up:<br>
There are several very well worked out plans to use space resources.<br>
<br>
It is interesting to note that the richest &amp; most accessible sources off-Earth, are the very same asteroidal bodies which are the biggest threats. We cannot see or track the tiny fragments (a 10 meter rock at 10km/sec is a nice little city-killer, and they hit all the time. It's just fortunate that we have a thick atmosphere, and 75% of the Earth is uninhabited water), but there should be nearly a thousand inner solar system asteroids bigger than 1km across.<br>
These have a slow approach velocity, which makes them a threat &amp; a promise: All but the biggest cometary body will detonate in the atmosphere. At very high speeds, a pressure wave builds up in front of the entering body. If the pressure exceeds the crush strength of the body, it breaks up in the air.<br>
A Near Earth Asteroid has a more nearly circular orbit around the Sun, with near 1 Earth year period. This by definition gives it a slow approach speed. These are far more likely to survive aeroentry intact, to reach the ground.<br>
This same fact makes them more easily accessible than our own Moon; a rocket can carry less fuel -hence more payload to/from them.<br>
The value of a tiny 800m rock if brought back to high Earth orbit would pay off the mission investment, and probably several large national debts.<br>
Forget the stupid hollywood ideas of blowing a rock up with nukes. If you fragment it, you're in even worse danger. Anything we plan to eliminate the danger requires at least as much effort as a mining/retrieval mission, and probably doesn't entail the profitability of mining the rock.<br>
<br>
There's no doubt about the richness of the resource, or the threat posed by it, and there's little doubt that it could be done profitably, with available technology. The only reason why it hasn't been proven &amp; tried in the past 30 years is desire &amp; political will. If asteroid resources &amp; space solar power would become the rich effort, and prove the death of oil &amp; it's impact on our economies, then it's in the best interest of the established interests to see that it doesn't happen.<br>
Every major decision made by the US &amp; most other governments, and nearly every facet of NASA's development &amp; history has been contradictory to allowing access to space to become economically viable.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://spacewatch.lpl.arizona.edu/">SpaceWatch</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is starting out, with pathetically small funding, but they're reporting new ones all the time.<br>
Read John Lewis: &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201154943/qid=1023250069/sr=1-5/ref=sr_1_5/002-1897403-8164832">Rain of Iron &amp; Ice</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot; and &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201328194/qid=1023250069/sr=1-4/ref=sr_1_4/002-1897403-8164832">Mining the Sky</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space-frontier.org/PROJECTS/ASTEROIDS/">Threat or a Promise</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot;<br>
&quot; (projections show evidence for) As many as 900 large asteroids (a kilometer or greater) in the inner solar system... according to a new study published in the June edition of the journal 'Science'...&quot;<br>
